This here 

    for (auto&amp; i : arr, arr2)

Won&#39;t work because that&#39;s not what the comma operator does. You can read about the comma operator [here][1]. In short, `arr, arr2` returns `arr2` so `for (auto&amp; i : arr, arr2)` is equivalent to `for (auto&amp; i : arr2)`.

Instead, since `arr` and `arr2` are `std::string`, you can just concatenate them with `+`:

```
for (auto&amp; i : arr + arr2)
{
	num.push_back(i);
}
```
  [1]: https://en.cppreference.com/w/cpp/language/operator_other

